  "text": "A second challenge to this view of stemness and niche function comes from vertebrate regeneration models such as the zebrafish fin, where transient niches are formed upon amputation that appear to induce dedifferentiation of cells in the remaining tissue. When the stem cell-like blastema cells eventually differentiate they obey strict lineage restriction [CITATION_1] . This demands the persistence of some form of memory of their previous nature, which is again not readily compatible with treating stemness as the diametral opposite of differentiation.",
